239
00:37:39.670 --> 00:37:46.670
Marcin Bugaj: So, hi everyone. Quick update on Project 3, the KVM Guest API standardization.

240
00:37:47.950 --> 00:37:56.509
Marcin Bugaj: We now have 5 accepted standards. Quick recap. The RISC-V target defines the ISA RV64IM.

241
00:37:56.760 --> 00:38:04.679
Marcin Bugaj: with unaligned data accesses, the I.O. interface gives guest programs a portable way to read private inputs and write public outputs.

242
00:38:05.160 --> 00:38:13.219
Marcin Bugaj: We have Cryptographic Accelerator's API, which is a C header for calling pre-compiled equivalent operations.

243
00:38:13.630 --> 00:38:20.709
Marcin Bugaj: Execution termination semantics says that successful execution may produce a proof.

244
00:38:20.890 --> 00:38:23.000
Marcin Bugaj: And failed ones cannot.

245
00:38:23.750 --> 00:38:34.800
Marcin Bugaj: And memory layout restrictions, which lets each vendor own their linker script, while source-level portability is preserved through

246
00:38:34.930 --> 00:38:36.720
Marcin Bugaj: The other standards.

247
00:38:37.320 --> 00:38:41.719
Marcin Bugaj: There are, currently,

248
00:38:41.890 --> 00:38:50.439
Marcin Bugaj: 3 more are currently in review, Memory Safety Guard Regions, and two new ones that I will cover next.

249
00:38:52.220 --> 00:39:01.740
Marcin Bugaj: So the first new standard is about what happens when a jump lands on a non-aligned address.

250
00:39:01.900 --> 00:39:07.629
Marcin Bugaj: Without a compressed instruction extension, RISC-V requires instructions to be 4-byte aligned.

251
00:39:07.950 --> 00:39:21.210
Marcin Bugaj: If a jump targets an unaligned access, the ISAR should raise an exception. The problem is that different ZKVMs, handle that exception differently. Common divergence from,

252
00:39:21.480 --> 00:39:28.760
Marcin Bugaj: The standard is rounding the address down to 4 bytes boundary, which could produce a valid proof.

253
00:39:29.070 --> 00:39:40.719
Marcin Bugaj: of a broken execution, so the standard closes that gap. It says that misaligned jumps must cause abnormal termination, no recovery, and no rounding.

254
00:39:41.020 --> 00:39:42.550
Marcin Bugaj: is permitted.

255
00:39:44.200 --> 00:39:51.909
Marcin Bugaj: The second new standard defines the runtime that vendors must ship alongside their ZKVMs.

256
00:39:52.230 --> 00:39:56.949
Marcin Bugaj: Two pieces, a single static library, and a linker script.

257
00:39:57.350 --> 00:40:03.969
Marcin Bugaj: The static library must contain start symbol, the I.O. functions, and the crypto accelerator implementation.

258
00:40:04.340 --> 00:40:08.200
Marcin Bugaj: Start function is responsible for setting up the stack.

259
00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:14.449
Marcin Bugaj: zeroing BSS section, preparing I.O, and then calling, main.

260
00:40:14.800 --> 00:40:19.470
Marcin Bugaj: On the application side, guest programs implement the main function.

261
00:40:19.940 --> 00:40:26.719
Marcin Bugaj: The value returned by the main must be translated to successful or abnormal termination.

262
00:40:26.980 --> 00:40:31.379
Marcin Bugaj: Consistently with the standard termination semantics.

263
00:40:31.490 --> 00:40:32.430
Marcin Bugaj: Standard.

264
00:40:33.240 --> 00:40:43.770
Marcin Bugaj: The linker script must be provided and must be compatible with both LD and LLVM's LLD.

265
00:40:43.970 --> 00:40:51.069
Marcin Bugaj: And must expose at least two standardized symbols, heap start and heap end.

266
00:40:51.350 --> 00:40:55.079
Marcin Bugaj: Those symbols are needed so that,

267
00:40:55.200 --> 00:41:00.359
Marcin Bugaj: The application can define its own memory allocator.

268
00:41:03.990 --> 00:41:10.140
Marcin Bugaj: We're also looking at whether to standardize U256.

269
00:41:10.570 --> 00:41:12.530
Marcin Bugaj: interface.

270
00:41:13.050 --> 00:41:19.240
Marcin Bugaj: We benchmarked 12 U-256 operations from one of these KVMs in isolation.

271
00:41:19.440 --> 00:41:22.460
Marcin Bugaj: And the summary is on the screen on the left.

272
00:41:23.580 --> 00:41:41.489
Marcin Bugaj: And the results are mixed. Multiplication delivers strong gains, 2 to even 6 times, depending on the operand size. Addition and subtractions are more modest, and several subtraction variants are actually slower than the software implementation.

273
00:41:41.760 --> 00:41:52.910
Marcin Bugaj: And assuming that performance profile, we then measured the impact on 500 realm minor blocks using only multiplication, division, and remainder accelerators.

274
00:41:53.300 --> 00:41:57.060
Marcin Bugaj: with a Reth-based Ethereum client.

275
00:41:57.550 --> 00:42:02.389
Marcin Bugaj: So the result is a very small, so to speak, negligible improvement.

276
00:42:03.150 --> 00:42:17.950
Marcin Bugaj: So that is, not settled. We need more investigation before proposing a standard, in particular, whether these poor numbers would hold with improved acceleration for addition and subtraction.

277
00:42:18.130 --> 00:42:24.160
Marcin Bugaj: And with the presence of acceleration for, beatwise operations.

278
00:42:26.440 --> 00:42:31.980
Marcin Bugaj: And, a reminder to vendors,

279
00:42:33.020 --> 00:42:39.540
Marcin Bugaj: So, all the KVMs are expected to migrate to RV64.

280
00:42:39.700 --> 00:42:44.039
Marcin Bugaj: Rust SDK must be no STD.

281
00:42:46.350 --> 00:43:05.809
Marcin Bugaj: And as it was mentioned, the I.O. and accelerator interfaces have to be bundled into the static library. Actually, there was some progress on the standard implementation in ZISK, so they… there's an implementation of no STD

282
00:43:05.890 --> 00:43:10.900
Marcin Bugaj: SDK, and also there is progress, on SP1's side.

283
00:43:11.180 --> 00:43:14.379
Marcin Bugaj: both links are on the screen.

284
00:43:14.660 --> 00:43:26.520
Marcin Bugaj: Yeah, also, if you need any help implementing those standards, Ethereum Foundation can provide engineering support.

